Lead Emergency Coordinator, Off-Site Senior Process Engineer, a General Manager, a Compliance Officer, Team Leader Operator, Maintenance & Repair Mechanics Lead and Plant Operators. However, during an emergency, all personnel within the plant are expected to take appropriate actions to ensure their safety and to facilitate a safe and efficient response to the incident.

Leaders of the Emergency Team will have the authority to put into action acceptable and valid procedures in the event of an emergency. The Emergency Team will respond immediately to any emergency that may arise at the Facility as a result of fires, explosions, natural disasters, or landfill gas leaks or emissions that may threaten public health and safety or the environment. Such responses will be carried out in accordance with the provisions of the Emergency Action Plan (EAP) and using all the personnel, equipment or machinery and materials that are available at the facility at the time of the event. At the time of the emergency, it will be determined if it is necessary to activate other agencies to provide support to it.

At a minimum, the following Initial Response Action Steps stated by the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) must be considered as soon as a dangerous situation becomes evident at the facility:
1.	Assess the situation, choose the appropriate response, and take immediate action;
2.	Take action to protect yourself first so you can in turn protect others;
3.	Take action to protect those in your immediate area;
4.	Communicate the need for others to take immediate protective actions;
5.	Notify emergency responders;
6.	Initiate the chosen response action and related emergency protocols found in your plan; and
7.	Triage injuries and apply emergency first aid as needed. 

